<subSubSection id="C30DB7F0FFBEBB1883D6BC72FB832A3F" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BA8E47BFFBEBB1883D6BC72FB832A3F" blockId="4.[151,1437,618,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB1883D6BC72FEC62C8E" bold="true" box="[151,274,618,644]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Slim and medium size (
<quantity id="4CEF499EFFBEBB188163BC72FDA32C8F" box="[546,631,618,645]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" unit="mm" value="25.0">25 mm</quantity>
). 
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB1881CBBC73FD1E2C8F" bold="true" box="[650,714,619,645]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Head</emphasis>
elongated from a frontal view, curved from a side view, curving downward and backward. The mouthparts between hypognathous and opisthognathous 
<typeStatus id="54AC5AD9FFBEBB188739BC97FB672CA3" box="[1144,1203,655,681]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">types</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="132CF8FEFFBEBB188785BC97FAF42CA3" box="[1220,1312,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
); very narrow space between antennal sockets, short fastigium, reduced and not visible ocelli, scapus, and pedicelus unarmed, maxillary palps moderately elongated. 
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188109BCCFFD752CFB" bold="true" box="[584,673,727,753]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Thorax</emphasis>
. Pronotum granular, sub-cylindrical (
<figureCitation id="132CF8FEFFBEBB188702BCCFFB4E2CFB" box="[1091,1178,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
); lateral lobes are three times longer than high, humeral notch undeveloped (
<figureCitation id="132CF8FEFFBEBB1881AABCE3FC922D1F" box="[747,838,763,789]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB18801BBCE2FC162D1E" bold="true" box="[858,962,762,788]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Sternum</emphasis>
. Prosternum armed with two conspicuous triangular spines. Upper lobe of mesosternum medium-sized, surrounded by lateral lobes with elevated subtriangular edges, covering the base of meso-coxae. Metasternum with no elevated lateral lobes, covered in the anterior margin by the upper lobe, metafurcal sulcus moderately elongated and not curving abruptly. 
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB1887D8BD7EFB312D8A" bold="true" box="[1177,1253,870,896]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Wings</emphasis>
. Brachypterous, tegminae covering up to the second abdominal segment (
<figureCitation id="132CF8FEFFBEBB18804EBD93FC882DAF" box="[783,860,907,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
A-B). 
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB1880E2BD93FC0F2DAF" bold="true" box="[931,987,907,933]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Legs</emphasis>
slim; front borders and middle legs well defined and delimited by a carina on each edge. Fore coxae armed with a dorsal spine, all coxae ventrally disarmed. 
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB1883D6BDCAFED82DE6" bold="true" box="[151,268,978,1004]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Abdomen</emphasis>
without modifications on the posterior edge. Tenth tergite narrow and moderately sclerosed (more than the other abdominal tergites). Cerci are very robust and armed inner by preapical spines (
<figureCitation id="132CF8FEFFBEBB1887CCBDEFFB082A1B" box="[1165,1244,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
C-D). Subgenital plate noticeably longer than wide, with articulated styles (
<figureCitation id="132CF8FEFFBEBB188061BA03FCAE2A3F" box="[800,890,1051,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-21@5.[211,1376,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pepumiri brasiliensis (Beier, 1962) n. comb. Male holotype. A. Habitus in lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively. C. Terminalia in lateral and D. Ventral view. “© by Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, U.S.A / G.A. Kung; published with permission.”" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6037017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6037017/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
). Female unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30DB7F0FFBEBB188386BA27FAFA2A53" box="[199,1326,1086,1114]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="type_taxon">
