by monotypy and original designation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30DB7F0FFBEBB188386BA7BFCC22ACF" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BA8E47BFFBEBB188386BA7BFCC22ACF" blockId="4.[151,1437,618,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188386BA7BFE9C2A77" bold="true" box="[199,328,1123,1149]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Etymology</emphasis>
. The name is an arbitrary combination of letters derived from two words in the Brazilian indigenous language Tupi: 
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188207BA9FFEA82AAB" box="[326,380,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">pépó</emphasis>
= wings + 
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB1882BCBA9FFDF82AAA" box="[509,556,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">mirĩ</emphasis>
= small, and it refers to the katydids’ small-sized wings. This name is neither non-Latin nor Greek, and gender is established as neuter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30DB7F0FFBEBB188386BAD6FCDA2AE0" box="[199,782,1230,1258]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="distribution">
