<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188386BAD6FEB52AE2" bold="true" box="[199,353,1230,1256]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingRegion id="49D32A99FFBEBB188226BAD7FE7F2AE3" box="[359,427,1231,1257]" country="Brazil" name="Goias" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Goiás</collectingRegion>
, Veadeiros (Brazilian Cerrado).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30DB7F0FFBEBB188386BAEAFD4928EB" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA8E47BFFBEBB188386BAEAFAE92827" blockId="4.[151,1437,618,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188386BAEAFE8F2B06" bold="true" box="[199,347,1266,1292]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Comparison</emphasis>
. The 
<taxonomicName id="4C179FF8FFBEBB1882DEBAEBFDD32B06" authority="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza, 2022" authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza" authorityYear="2022" box="[415,519,1267,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pepumiri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB1882DEBAEBFDD32B06" box="[415,519,1267,1292]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Pepumiri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188150BAEBFDB62B07" bold="true" box="[529,610,1267,1293]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2508512FFBEBB188150BAEBFDB62B07" box="[529,610,1267,1293]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, characteristics are distinctive and well-differentiated from other genera from the tribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C179FF8FFBEBB18827EBB0FFE632B3B" authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1895" box="[319,439,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pleminiini">Pleminiini</taxonomicName>
. Compared to other genera of brachypterous species, such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C179FF8FFBEBB18873FBB0FFB282B3B" authorityName="Redtenbacher" authorityYear="1895" box="[1150,1276,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB18873FBB0FFB282B3B" box="[1150,1276,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Dasyscelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C179FF8FFBEBB188676BB0FFED82B5F" authority="Stal, 1874" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1874" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pleminia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188676BB0FFA482B3B" box="[1335,1436,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Pleminia</emphasis>
Stål, 1874
</taxonomicName>
, these specimens have triangular and lamellar spines on the legs. Furthermore, the head and mouthparts are hypognate, unlike the 
<taxonomicName id="4C179FF8FFBEBB1882F9BB47FDF42B72" authority="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza, 2022" authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza" authorityYear="2022" box="[440,544,1375,1400]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pepumiri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB1882F9BB47FDF42B72" box="[440,544,1375,1400]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Pepumiri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188166BB47FDA12B73" bold="true" box="[551,629,1375,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2508512FFBEBB188166BB47FDA12B73" box="[551,629,1375,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, located behind, almost on the thoracic sternites. The tegminae venation in 
<taxonomicName id="4C179FF8FFBEBB1883F5BB9BFEE62B97" authorityName="Redtenbacher" authorityYear="1895" box="[180,306,1411,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB1883F5BB9BFEE62B97" box="[180,306,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Dasyscelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C179FF8FFBEBB18822BBB9BFE1B2B97" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1874" box="[362,463,1411,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pleminia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB18822BBB9BFE1B2B97" box="[362,463,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Pleminia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is less reticulated and has larger spaces between the longitudinal and transverse veins. Known males from the last two genera have short and slightly thickened stridulation crest, in contrast to 
<taxonomicName id="4C179FF8FFBEBB188654BBBFFF612BEE" authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Beier" baseAuthorityYear="1962" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pepumiri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188654BBBFFF612BEE" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">P. brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB1883FABBD3FEF52BEF" bold="true" box="[187,289,1483,1509]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2508512FFBEBB1883FABBD3FEF52BEF" box="[187,289,1483,1509]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" rank="species">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, which have an elongated and thickened stridulation crest. The cerci of the males of this new genus are very distinctive because the cerci of other genera compared here are cylindrical, with similar thickness throughout their length and a distal spine, while 
<taxonomicName id="4C179FF8FFBEBB188172B80BFD042827" authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Beier" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[563,720,1555,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pepumiri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188172B80BFD042827" box="[563,720,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">P. brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188196B80BFCE92827" bold="true" box="[727,829,1555,1581]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2508512FFBEBB188196B80BFCE92827" box="[727,829,1555,1581]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" rank="species">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
has thickened cerci and two preapical spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA8E47BFFBEBB188386B82EFD4928EB" blockId="4.[151,1437,618,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188386B82EFE9B285A" bold="true" box="[199,335,1590,1616]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Comments.</emphasis>
We include 
<taxonomicName id="4C179FF8FFBEBB18829FB82FFC5A285B" authority="Beier, 1962" authorityName="Beier" authorityYear="1962" box="[478,910,1591,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Dasyscelidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB18829FB82FFCD7285B" box="[478,771,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Dasyscelidius brasiliensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF86998AFFBEBB18804AB82FFC5A285B" author="Beier, M." box="[779,910,1591,1617]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" pagination="468" refId="ref3769" refString="Beier, M. (1962) Orthoptera Tettigoniidae (Pseudophyllinae I). In: Mertens, R., Hennig, W. &amp; Wermuth, H. (Eds.), Das Tierreich. Vol. 73. Walter de Gruyter &amp; Co., Berlin, pp. 468." type="book chapter" year="1962">Beier, 1962</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
as the only known species and as a new combination of 
<taxonomicName id="4C179FF8FFBEBB18825BB843FE56287E" authority="This" authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza" authorityYear="2022" box="[282,386,1627,1652]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pepumiri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB18825BB843FE56287E" box="[282,386,1627,1652]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Pepumiri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB1882CBB843FE0E287F" bold="true" box="[394,474,1627,1653]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2508512FFBEBB1882CBB843FE0E287F" box="[394,474,1627,1653]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
This species inhabits the Cerrado ecoregion in 
<collectingCountry id="F300A4EBFFBEBB1880B4B843FBEA287F" box="[1013,1086,1627,1653]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Brazil</collectingCountry>
: vast savanna whose higher elevation areas have humid conditions, ideal for species such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C179FF8FFBEBB188014B867FB352890" authority="(Beier, 1962)" authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Poveda &amp; Pulido &amp; Ariza" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Beier" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[853,1249,1663,1690]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pepumiri" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB188014B867FB912893" box="[853,1093,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">Pepumiri brasiliensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF86998AFFBEBB188715B867FB0D2890" author="Beier, M." box="[1108,1241,1663,1690]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" pagination="468" refId="ref3769" refString="Beier, M. (1962) Orthoptera Tettigoniidae (Pseudophyllinae I). In: Mertens, R., Hennig, W. &amp; Wermuth, H. (Eds.), Das Tierreich. Vol. 73. Walter de Gruyter &amp; Co., Berlin, pp. 468." type="book chapter" year="1962">Beier, 1962</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9633869FFBEBB1887A9B867FA9A2893" bold="true" box="[1256,1358,1663,1689]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2508512FFBEBB1887A9B867FA9A2893" box="[1256,1358,1663,1689]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" rank="species">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
In this way, it is an area that differs from the rest of the lowlands of the Brazilian Cerrado, harboring a significant degree of endemism (
<bibRefCitation id="EF86998AFFBEBB188276B8DFFE3028EB" author="Werneck, F. P." box="[311,484,1735,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" pagination="1630 - 1648" refId="ref4320" refString="Werneck, F. P. (2011) The diversification of eastern South American open vegetation biomes: Historical biogeography and perspectives. Quaternary Science Reviews, 30, 1630 - 1648. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. quascirev. 2011.03.009" type="journal article" year="2011">Werneck, 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF86998AFFBEBB1882AEB8DFFD4528EB" author="Luebert, F." box="[495,657,1735,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="133" pagination="1 - 4" refId="ref4280" refString="Luebert, F. (2021) The two South American dry diagonals. Frontiers of Biogeography, 13 (4), 1 - 4. https: // doi. org / 10.21425 / F 5 FBG 51267" type="journal article" year="2021">Luebert, 2021</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
